## Sprint 3 — People & Relationship Graph Domain
**Duration:** 2 weeks | **Goal:** The core data model of the entire system is solid and queryable

### What to Deliver
- `Contact` aggregate with all its layers: basic facts, relationship metadata, closeness tier, life chapters. Domain layer only — no Spring
- `Relationship` entity connecting two contacts with a relationship type. This is a self-referencing join on the contacts table
- Flyway migrations for `contacts`, `contact_life_chapters`, and `contact_relationships` tables
- CRUD API for contacts and relationships via REST — this is the one domain where CRUD is the right pattern, so move fast on it
- The graph traversal query: given a contact ID, return all contacts within N hops. Write this as a recursive CTE in PostgreSQL. Expose it as a `GET /contacts/{id}/network?depth=2` endpoint
- A `ContactQueryFacade` interface in `right-hand-people`'s application layer — this is the only way any other module will ever read contact data. Even though nothing uses it yet, define it now
- Load test the graph traversal with 1,000 contacts and 5,000 relationships seeded via a Flyway test migration. Query must return in under 100ms. Add a partial index if it doesn't

### Where to Slow Down 🔴
The recursive CTE query. Understand `WITH RECURSIVE`, the base case, the recursive case, and the cycle prevention clause. Run `EXPLAIN ANALYZE` on it before and after adding the index. Read what the query planner is doing. This is one of the most valuable SQL skills you'll gain in this project.

### Move Fast On 🟢
The REST CRUD for contacts. Basic Spring MVC controller, service, repository. No special patterns needed here.

### Architecture Checkpoint
*Why is `ContactQueryFacade` an interface defined in the `application` layer of `right-hand-people` rather than just letting other modules call the repository directly? What would break if you skipped it?*

