## Sprint 10 — Observability, Hardening & The Architecture Review
**Duration:** 2 weeks | **Goal:** The system is production-honest and you can demonstrate mastery of every decision made

### What to Deliver
- Micrometer metrics wired to Prometheus for: nudge engine run duration, LLM API call latency and failure rate, Kafka consumer lag per topic, relationship health score distribution as a histogram, draft generation end-to-end latency (from `POST /drafts` to `READY` status)
- OpenTelemetry distributed tracing: trace a single `POST /interactions` call through the outbox poller, through Kafka, through the fact extractor consumer, through the life fact writer, and into the nudge evaluator. All spans connected under one trace ID
- Grafana dashboard with 5 panels: system health overview, LLM API performance, Kafka consumer lag, nudge engine stats, and relationship health distribution across all contacts
- Application-layer encryption for `PRIVATE`-tier life facts: AES-256 encryption of the fact value before Postgres write, decryption on read. Key derived from a user secret stored in Redis session. Write a test that dumps the raw Postgres row and confirms the value column is unreadable
- ArchUnit full coverage: every architectural rule enforced at test time. Run the suite and fix every violation. The suite becomes a non-negotiable part of the build
- A load test using Gatling: simulate 6 months of relationship activity — 1,000 contacts, 10,000 interactions logged, nudge engine run, 500 draft requests — and verify no endpoint degrades beyond acceptable thresholds
- Write a 2-page architecture decision record (ADR) for the three most consequential decisions you made: why modular monolith over microservices, why the outbox pattern for event publishing, and why PostgreSQL full-text search over Elasticsearch. Each ADR has: context, decision, consequences (positive and negative)

### Where to Slow Down 🔴
The ADR writing. This is not documentation for its own sake. The act of writing why you made each decision, what alternatives you considered, and what you gave up forces you to understand your own system at a level most engineers never reach. If you can't write a coherent ADR for a decision, you don't fully understand it yet. Go back and re-examine it until you can.

The distributed trace. Getting a trace that spans from an HTTP request through Kafka through two consumers requires understanding how OpenTelemetry propagates context across async boundaries via Kafka headers. This is non-trivial and genuinely teaches you something about distributed observability.

### Move Fast On 🟢
The Grafana dashboard. Pick five metrics, wire up five panels, move on. Dashboards are iterative.

### Architecture Checkpoint — Final
*Someone hands you this system and asks: "Where would this break first if the user's contact list grew to 10,000 people?" Walk through every component — the nudge engine batch job, the graph traversal query, the timeline pagination, the LLM draft assembly, the health score computation — and give a specific, technically grounded answer for each one.*

